snippet: Enrollment of Latinos in the new health care law has fallen strikingly below the hopes of the law’s proponents, prompting officials to rush to expand marketing efforts.
abstract: Enrollment of Latinos in the new health care law has fallen strikingly below the hopes of the law’s proponents, prompting officials to rush to expand marketing efforts; California stands out as most troubling case, proponents of law say, because it has most Latinos of any state and has worked hard to enroll them; some illegal immigrants fear deportation.

byline.original: By JENNIFER MEDINA and ABBY GOODNOUGH

lead_paragraph: Enrollment of Latinos in the new health care law has fallen strikingly below the hopes of the law’s proponents, prompting officials to rush to expand marketing efforts.

headline.main: States Struggle to Add Latinos to Health Rolls
headline.print_headline: States Struggle to Add Latinos to Health Rolls
